The Holiday baking guide

Tips & tricks for baking the best holiday cookies.

Be careful not to overmix your cookie dough. There are two steps in the cookie-making process where you want to watch out for overmixing: when you're combining the butter, sugar & eggs, & when you're incorporating the wet & dry ingredients together. If you overmix the butter, sugar & egg mixture, you'll introduce too much air into the dough, resulting in flat cookies. Overworking the dough when mixing the wet & dry ingredients can lead to gluten development, which makes for tough cookies. In general, use the minimum amount of mixing necessary to ensure your ingredients are fully combined. Refrigerate your cookie dough before baking. The chilling process firms the fat (like butter) in the cookie dough, allows the sugar to absorb moisture & deepens flavor—resulting in chewier, better-tasting cookies. You can chill the dough for as little as 30 minutes & up to 24 hours in the fridge. Use a cookie scoop for a picture-perfect bake. A cookie scoop is a handy tool for ensuring all your cookies are uniform & baked at the same rate. For easy cleanup, don’t forget to line your sheet pan with parchment paper. Don’t rely on the timer alone. There’s nothing worse than dry, overbaked cookies—so keep a close eye on them while they’re in the oven, especially toward the end of the suggested baking time. A few signs that your cookies are done? The dough will have lost its glossy sheen & the edges should be lightly golden & set. Once the cookies are out of the oven, let the residual heat from the baking sheet cool before transferring to a wire rack to cool completely.

What are some ideas for decorating holiday cookies?

Spread cookies with sweet, store-bought frosting. Ready-to-use frosting is one of the fastest, easiest ways to add an extra dash of festive flair to your cookies. Mix & match different frosting colors, then top with your favorite sprinkles, sanding sugar or crushed peppermint candy. For smoothly spreading the frosting, use an offset spatula; you can also use a piping bag (or zip-top bag with a small hole cut in the corner) to create different shapes & designs. Dip holiday cookies in icing or melted baking chocolate. This is another simple way to elevate your treats. Prep the icing or melted chocolate, place it in a shallow bowl, then dip your cookies into the icing or chocolate (you can dip the top of the cookie or dunk it halfway in) & transfer to a parchment paper-lined sheet pan. Before the icing or chocolate hardens, decorate your dipped cookies with sprinkles, sanding sugar, crushed peppermint candy, toasted & crushed nuts or sweetened coconut flakes. Try your hand at decorating with royal icing. To decorate sugar cookies with more complex designs, you can use royal icing in different colors, along with piping bags & tips. When preparing your royal icing, add water slowly until you reach your desired consistency: thinner for the flooding technique, thicker for more three-dimensional designs.

How should I store my baked cookies?

Make sure the cookies are completely cooled before storing at room temperature in an airtight container. Pro tip: Store different flavors separately. Over time, strongly flavored cookies like peanut butter or mint will seep into the other cookies, so store each flavor in its own container if possible. Homemade cookies can be stored in an airtight container for 2–3 weeks at room temperature, or up to two months in the refrigerator. You can also keep fully baked cookies, individually wrapped in plastic wrap & stored in an airtight container, in the freezer for 8–12 months. When you’re ready to serve, remove the cookies from the container & plastic wrap & thaw at room temperature; once thawed, you can warm them up in the microwave or oven.

How can I package & mail cookies for the holidays?

Careful packing can mean the difference between receiving a box of joyful cookies or a box of buttery crumbs (just as yummy, but less pretty). If you’re planning to ship cookies, bake sturdy treats: Brownies, blondies, bar cookies, shortbread, chewy cookies (like oatmeal raisin or molasses), rum balls & sandwich cookies are all good choices. They hold up better than delicate, thin cookies like lace cookies or wafers—give these to your neighbors instead. Package up your cookies in tins or airtight plastic containers, which won’t get crushed during shipping or show butter stains. Sturdy bakery boxes work too, if you line them with plastic or parchment before packing. Use tissue paper to envelope & cushion the cookies inside their tin or box so they don’t rattle around. Fill the tin to the top with cookies, cover with more tissue & close the lid. To test if the cookies are snugly in the box, gently shake it—you shouldn’t feel the cookies move or bounce. Once your assembled cookie container is packed up in a cardboard shipping box, fill it with bubble wrap or other packing filler for extra protection.

About Baking Essentials - Walmart.com

What's the difference between baking soda and baking powder?

Baking soda's scientific name is sodium bicarbonate. Add liquid and acid ingredients to baking soda recipes to make doughs and batters rise in the oven. Baking powder is sodium bicarbonate with acidic agents already in the powder mix, so it only requires liquid in the recipe to make cakes and other baked goods rise.

Which cooking oil is best for baking?

For the best flavor in cakes and other sweetened baked goods, use a light vegetable oil like canola oil. For savory breads, use a more flavorful oil like olive oil. For high-heat baking, use peanut oil or sunflower oil, which can both handle high temperatures.

How do I use coconut flour?

Coconut flour is gluten-free and keto friendly with a much denser and more absorbent texture than standard baking flour. Don't try a straight conversion from standard flour to coconut flour, but add up to one part coconut flour for four parts standard flour. Try a few coconut flour recipes to gain confidence with this unique baking ingredient.
